
This directory is intended for PlatformIO Test Runner and project tests.

Unit Testing is a software testing method by which individual units of
source code, sets of one or more MCU program modules together with associated
control data, usage procedures, and operating procedures, are tested to
determine whether they are fit for use. Unit testing finds problems early
in the development cycle.

More information about PlatformIO Unit Testing:
- https://docs.platformio.org/en/latest/advanced/unit-testing/index.html

## Hardware resilience tests

### Platform build matrix

Compile every supported firmware target without uploading:

```bash
test/build_platform_matrix.sh
```

The matrix currently contains:

- `m5stack-capsule-v1_1`: Capsule pins, power hold, RTC and internal IMU.
- `m5stack-stamps3-generic`: bare StampS3/custom carrier without Capsule assumptions.
- `esp32-s3-devkitc-1`: generic ESP32-S3 DevKitC target.

Build testing catches conditional-compilation and dependency problems. Each
physical board should also run the serial hardware tests because compilation
cannot validate wiring, I2C pull-ups, SD signal integrity or sensor presence.

Install the one host dependency:

```bash
python3 -m pip install -r test/requirements-hardware.txt
```

Stop any PlatformIO serial monitor before running a test; only one process can
own the serial port. Flash the current firmware, exit the monitor, then run a
scenario. Each command exits zero on pass and nonzero on failure.

Baseline Capsule with all sensors:

```bash
python3 test/hardware_resilience_test.py sensor-matrix \
  --airspeed present --bmp present --temperature present --imu present
```

The equivalent named profile is:

```bash
python3 test/hardware_resilience_test.py sensor-matrix --profile capsule-all
```

Examples for other combinations:

```bash
# Capsule alone, with no external sensors
python3 test/hardware_resilience_test.py sensor-matrix \
  --airspeed absent --bmp absent --temperature absent --imu present

# BMP280 or BMP390 only, plus the Capsule IMU
python3 test/hardware_resilience_test.py sensor-matrix \
  --airspeed absent --bmp present --temperature present --imu present
```

Available profiles are `capsule-all`, `capsule-bare`, `stamp-generic`, and
`devkit-bare`. Individual `--airspeed`, `--bmp`, `--temperature`, and `--imu`
arguments override a profile when explicitly set to `present` or `absent`.

Guided fault tests:

```bash
python3 test/hardware_resilience_test.py i2c-interruption
python3 test/hardware_resilience_test.py sd-removal
python3 test/hardware_resilience_test.py sd-full
python3 test/hardware_resilience_test.py corrupt-filesystem
python3 test/hardware_resilience_test.py queue-saturation --duration 120
```

The SD-full test expects a mounted card with less than one 6 KB RAM log buffer
of free space. The corrupt-filesystem test expects a deliberately invalid
LittleFS partition and no SD card. Those tests do not corrupt or fill media
themselves.

Run the serial-parser unit tests without hardware:

```bash
python3 -m unittest discover -s test -p 'test_hardware_resilience_parser.py'
```

Run the ordinary all-sensors check followed by a 60-second queue soak:

```bash
test/run_hardware_tests.sh /dev/cu.usbmodem11101
```


ear/flashmon.sh

pio run --target upload --upload-port /dev/cu.usbmodem11101
pio device monitor --port /dev/cu.usbmodem11101 --baud 115200


pio run --target upload --upload-port /dev/cu.usbmodem11101 && sleep 2 && pio device monitor --port /dev/cu.usbmodem11101 --baud 115200

lsof /dev/cu.usbmodem11101
Show only its process ID:
lsof -t /dev/cu.usbmodem11101
Stop that process gracefully:
kill "$(lsof -t /dev/cu.usbmodem11101)"
If it refuses to stop, force it:
kill -9 "$(lsof -t /dev/cu.usbmodem11101)"
